Cryptocurrency is not just a financial tool; it is a shift in how humans understand value, trust, and ownership. For decades, money has relied on centralized institutions—banks, governments, and intermediaries that validate, store, and control transactions. Crypto challenges this model by introducing decentralized systems where trust is replaced by code and transparency.

At its core, cryptocurrency is built on blockchain technology. A blockchain is a distributed ledger that records transactions across many computers, making it nearly impossible to alter past data without consensus. This creates a system where no single entity has full control, and where verification is shared among participants.
